<br>
The UN should, but they dont sadly.  That does not mean that the US should start doing it though.  <br>
<br>
---<br>
<br>
Slightly offtopic but pertains to UN and resolutions:<br>
<br>
So, what happens when the UN give a non-member country a resolution to follow and it's unfair.  Look at it from Iraq's perspective. (and dont start with the &quot;kanelan loves iraq thing&quot; cause i don't --- just making a point.  this can be generalized to any country)  Iraq invades another county, BAD Iraq, <br>
/slap Iraq_001<br>
/sanctions on<br>
/pause 5 years<br>
Iraq_001&gt; Can we get off sanctions yet?<br>
UN_001&gt; We'll meet in tropical_city001 next year to decide<br>
Iraq_001 says&gt; Please!!!<br>
UN_001&gt; Meeting scheduled for next year, bug off.<br>
/em Iraq_001 shoots at UN planes flying over their county.<br>
Iraq_001&gt; We want off sanctions NOW !<br>
/slap Iraq_001<br>
/sanctions double<br>
/pause 5 years<br>
Iraq_001&gt; Can we get off sanctions yet?<br>
UN_001&gt; You shot at us, hell no!<br>
<br>
rince repeat...<br>
<br>
/em Iraq_001 ponders the situation.<br>
/em Iraq_001 thinks that the UN can bugger off.  Never liked em anyway.<br>
/em Iraq_001 shoots at more planes and dreams up ways to pay back the evil soul behind the sanctions (US)<br>
<br>
Makes sense doen't it?  Now, dont get me wrong - Saddam + regime is BAD for doing what they do, but from their perspective they're leading a country and since they aren't a member of the UN, why should they follow their rules?!<br>
<br>
IMO - we F*ck*d up 15 years ago when we invaded Iraq.  We left a dictatorship in power that hated the UN/US and then expected them to follow the sanctions we imposed on them.  Is this Iraq's fault?  No, it's the US policy makers.  Now the next generation of US policy makers want to go make war again to fix the problem..  /sigh  It's our (US's) own damn fault.  <br>
<br>
US foreign policy blows.  1/2 the time we stick our noses in something where it doesnt belong and the other 49% of the time we f*ck it up when we stick it in when it *might* belong.<br>
<br>
So, why not just invade and finish what we started?  Becuse it's a little late 15 years after the fact.  Other countries have &quot;forgotten&quot; (or at least lessened their anger) about the invasion of Kuait.<br>
<br>
So, back to the point about Iraq wanting off sanctions..  Why are they on them anyway?  Beacause they shoot at us flying over THEIR country?  Because they invaded Kuait almost 15 years ago?  How much should a country have to endure after they F*ck up like Iraq did?  How long did Germany wait after WW1?  Hmm wait a sec, they only stopped paying reparations when they said F*ck you to the US+allies.  &quot;/start war machine WW2&quot;  History repeats itself again.  /sigh  When will the US/UN policy makers learn that sanctions do very little.  Look at Cuba.  /sigh again<br>
<br>
<br>
Disclaimer:  The above paragraphs should bring up lots of questions and though provoking ideas.  I'm not saying that war is needed to finish the job.  I'm not saying that a war wouldn't &quot;fix&quot; the problem.  Just think about why the US/UN is in the situation that they are in.  Who put them there?  How did the UN/US help themselves?  How did the UN/US hurt themselves?  There's a reson we;re arguing about wheather to go to war or not on this post, but WHAT caused it to get to this point?  Is it all Iraq's fault?  Is it partly Iraq's fault and partly US/UN's fault?  Is it all US/UN's fault?<br>
<br>
Disclaimer #2:  This sat on my desk for an hour before it hit submit, damn meetings.... <p>**********Quellious*********<br>
